LESSON 2: Row Context vs Filter Context (the heart of DAX)

ðŸ§  ROW CONTEXT

Row context = DAX looks at one row at a time.

This exists in:

âœ” Calculated Columns
âœ” Iterators (SUMX, AVERAGEX, FILTER etc.)

Example (calculated column):

Profit = Sales[SalesAmount] - Sales[Cost]


DAX goes row by row:

Amount	Cost	Profit
200	150	50
300	200	100
500	300	200

That is row context.

ðŸŽ¯ FILTER CONTEXT

Filter context = filters coming from:

âœ” slicers
âœ” visual
âœ” page filters
âœ” report filters
âœ” CALCULATE()

Example:

Total Revenue = SUM(Sales[SalesAmount])


If the user selects:

Product = â€œAâ€

Region = â€œIndiaâ€

Year = 2023

The measure will only sum those rows.

That's filter context.

ðŸŒŸ Why CALCULATE() is god-level?

Because CALCULATE changes filter context.

Example:

Total Revenue All Products =
CALCULATE(
    SUM(Sales[SalesAmount]),
    ALL(Sales[Product])
)

This removes the product filter.
# calculate  - is overpowering on filters applied
Exercise:
Write DAX for the following:

1. Sales for year 2024
sales_2024 = calculate(sum(sales[amount]), filter(sales, sales[year] = 2024))

2. Total Sales ignoring all filters

(Hint: use ALL)

3. Sales for orders where Quantity > 5

